The Great Hurricane of 1780 was an extraordinarily destructive storm that struck the Caribbean. Its precise origin and strength remain uncertain due to the absence of modern storm-tracking technology at the time. 

The hurricane is believed to have first made landfall in Barbados, subsequently ravaging other parts of the eastern Caribbean over the following week. The islands of Barbados, Martinique, and St. Lucia were particularly hard hit, suffering thousands of casualties and widespread destruction of property. 

During this period, both Great Britain and France were engaged in the American Revolutionary War, and numerous naval vessels from both nations were present in the Caribbean. Many of these ships were lost to the storm, further complicating wartime efforts.

Despite numerous deadly hurricanes since 1780, only Hurricane Mitch in 1998, which resulted in over 11,000 deaths in Central America, has come close to the catastrophic toll of the Great Hurricane.

Name: Smith, Adam
text:
I released a new statement calling for stability and de-escalation of tensions in the Middle East.

The continued conflict in Gaza, the conflict between Israel and Hezbollah, the ongoing proxy war with Iran, the fight with the Houthis, the fight with Iranian proxies in Syria ‚Äî all of these conflicts are devastating to the civilian population and continue to place significant numbers of civilians at risk across Gaza, the West Bank, Israel, Lebanon, Yemen, and elsewhere. Each of these conflicts runs the risk of massive escalation.

The international community needs to recognize that Iran remains the main driver of this conflict. They have backed Hezbollah, the Houthis, Hamas, and other Shia militias in Iraq and Syria for years. Israel is threatened by these extremist proxy groups that continually try to exterminate their country, some of whom explicitly have as their motto ‚Äúdeath to the U.S., death to Israel, a curse upon the Jews.‚Äù This rhetoric and their attempts to destroy Israel through missiles or terrorist attacks is abominable. Israel has a right to defend itself against these existential threats. However, even as we understand Israel‚Äôs motivations to fight back against these extremist groups, the risk of escalation and the cost to the civilian population puts Israel and others in the region at even greater risk.

The only way out of this regional conflict is to have a coalition of the U.S., Israel, Saudi Arabia, U.A.E., Jordan, Qatar, and other Arab states as a deterrence to Iran. That will never happen if there isn‚Äôt a future for the Palestinian people. While I understand Israel‚Äôs response to the threat from Iran and all of their proxies, I am adamantly opposed to Israel‚Äôs approach to the West Bank. It is unacceptable for Israel to continue to press claims into the West Bank that have no support in international law. It is also completely unacceptable for Israel to not have a plan for a post-Hamas future for Palestinians in Gaza. Peace will never be achieved unless there is a future for the Palestinian people.

Ceasefire negotiations have never been more important. I support the Biden Administration‚Äôs continued efforts to bring parties in the region together to achieve that ceasefire in Gaza, Lebanon, and Israel.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
As Taiwan celebrates this 113th ROC National Day, we proudly stand in solidarity with our friends and ally, Taiwan. This January, as Chairman of the National Intelligence Subcommittee of the House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence and a Member of the NATO Parliamentary Assembly, I traveled to Taiwan to lead key intelligence meetings with their officials and further strengthen our partnership standing together in defense of freedom.

Taiwan stands on the frontlines of a global battle between good and evil, democracy and tyranny. The United States will always stand with Taiwan and never waver in our commitment to defend the principles of liberty, justice, and the values we hold dear. Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1992, Deion Sanders attempted to make sports history by playing in both the NFL and MLB on the same day. 

‚ÄúPrime Time‚Äù began his day with the Atlanta Falcons facing the Miami Dolphins at the Orange Bowl, where they lost 21-17. In that game, Sanders showcased his versatility by returning two kicks, a punt, and catching a nine-yard pass, all while contributing to a defense tasked with containing the legendary Dan Marino.

Immediately after the game, Sanders flew to Pittsburgh for Game 5 of the 1992 NLCS with the Atlanta Braves. He arrived still in his Falcons gear, unprepared for the 53-degree weather. Although he did not see any action in the Braves' 7-1 defeat to the Pirates, his mere presence was historic; had he played, he would have been the first athlete to compete in two major American professional sports on the same day.

A week later, Sanders had another opportunity to make history, with the Falcons facing the 49ers and the Braves hosting the Blue Jays for Game 2 of the World Series. However, he opted to remain in Atlanta, starting in left field. He recorded one hit and two walks in a closely contested 5-4 loss to the Blue Jays. While his attempts to play in both leagues on the same day didn‚Äôt succeed, Sanders‚Äôs dual-sport aspirations left a lasting mark on sports history.

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
Friday in the First

At just 19 years old, Lance, a native of Franklin County and NC State University student, embodies the spirit of 4-H through his commitment to service and leadership‚Äîa recipient of the prestigious NC State University Park Scholarship, he has spent over 12 years actively participating in the NC Cooperative Extension‚Äôs 4-H Program, starting with 4-H Sizzling Summer Sessions at just six years old.

Lance‚Äôs leadership journey has taken him through various roles at the county, district, and state levels, including serving as a Northeast District Officer and NC 4-H State Officer. His recent induction into the North Carolina 4-H Honor Club during the NC 4-H Congress ceremony highlights his significant leadership, civic engagement, and community service achievements. As we recognize National 4-H Week, Lance‚Äôs accomplishments remind us of the vital role that young leaders play in shaping their communities and inspiring others to create positive change.

In honor of National 4-H Week, we are highlighting the impact that dedicated youth like Lance have on our communities. 

#FridaySpotlight

Meet this week‚Äôs Hometown Heroes‚ÄîChristy Murphy and the incredible @bcdragonboat Women's Senior A Team.
 
This is not just a tale of athletic triumph, although their accomplishments on the water are nothing short of extraordinary. Led by the incredible Chris and Jaquelyn Wetzel, the Bucks County Dragon Boat Association (BCDBA) recently competed on the world stage in Ravenna, Italy, against the top dragon boat teams from around the globe. They brought home two silver medals and a gold‚Äîan achievement that speaks volumes about their talent, determination, and dedication. But as impressive as these victories are, their most profound accomplishment wasn‚Äôt measured in medals but in saving a life.
 
On September 3rd, following a grueling 2000-meter race that earned them the silver medal, Christy Murphy and her Women's Senior A teammates were paddling back to the docks when they saw a man in the water, struggling to stay afloat. It was a moment that could have paralyzed many with fear, but instead, it became a moment of pure heroism. Without a second thought, Christy sprang into action, drawing on the same strength, precision, and teamwork that had carried them through the race. She knew every second was crucial.
 
With her teammates rallying behind her, Christy plunged into the water and swam to the struggling man. With the help of her teammates, they pulled him onto their boat and safely transferred him to the motor rescue they had flagged down. On that day, this remarkable group of Bucks County women did not just prove themselves as world-class athletes‚Äîthey showed us all what it means to be true heroes. This extraordinary and selfless act transcends any medal or title, reminding us of the power of human connection, teamwork, and what we are capable of when we come together.
 
Please join me in giving a well-deserved round of applause to Christy, Women's Senior A Team, and the entire Bucks County Dragon Boat Association!

Name: Hirono, Mazie K.
text:
Great news‚Äî@FEMA just announced it will be extending housing assistance to Maui wildfire survivors for an additional year.

The extension of the Individuals and Households Program (IHP), including Financial Assistance and Direct Temporary Housing Assistance was originally set to end on February 10, 2025, but will now be extended to February 10, 2026.

There are currently 1,194 households occupying FEMA-provided units, and with this extension, survivors housed in temporary FEMA units will be able to continue working on their permanent housing plan and start paying rent, depending on their financial ability.

Occupants who provide documentation of their post-disaster income that meets or is below HUD‚Äôs very low-income limit will qualify for fully reduced rent of $50 per month without having to appeal and submit documentation of pre- or post-disaster housing costs.

Occupants with household incomes above the HUD very low-income limit will only have to provide documentation of post-disaster housing costs for FEMA to evaluate the amount of rent to be charged based on their financial ability.

FEMA will conduct outreach to assist occupants of temporary housing units with the documentation necessary to evaluate their ability to pay.

For more information on temporary housing, call the Individual Assistance Housing Hotline at 808-784-1600, contact 2-1-1 to reach the disaster case management program, or call FEMA Helpline at 800-621-3362 for assistance in other languages. You can also get help in-person at Lahaina Gateway  (next to Ace Hardware) or the CNHA Office next to Maui Mall in Kahului.

I thank FEMA for its flexibility and attention to helping Lahaina recover and rebuild, guided by the voices and values of the people of Maui.

Congratulations to Josh Spaar of Troop 108, Justin Gontarek of Troop 147, Orion San Jose of Troop 13, and Ryan Quanstrom of Troop 29 on earning the esteemed rank of Eagle Scout! This achievement highlights their leadership, character, and dedication to service.
 
Each one of these young men has made impactful contributions through their Eagle Scout projects. Josh built an enclosed vegetable garden with raised beds and wheelchair-accessible tables for The Open Link, a community agency and food bank in Pennsburg; Justin replaced the flags at Holland Elementary School, enhancing the school grounds; Orion painted 27 curbs yellow around fire hydrants in Trumbauersville Borough, improving safety for residents during emergencies; and Ryan constructed a new footbridge over Mill Race in Newtown.
 
Join me in celebrating these outstanding young leaders and wishing them success in their future endeavors!

Name: Rounds, Mike
text:
I just received word that the Department of Justice has heard the concerns of tribal leaders in South Dakota and are taking steps to address the public safety crisis. 

Following the meeting that my office facilitated with Attorney General Merrick Garland in South Dakota, the DOJ will be issuing a number of proposals requested by tribal leaders in South Dakota, including changes to the funding mechanisms that the federal government uses to support public safety programs. The DOJ intends on holding formal consultation sessions with tribes to determine the final path forward. 

This is great news and a good first step as we look to restore law and order on reservations in South Dakota and across the Great Plains. I sincerely thank all of the tribal leaders who participated in our roundtable with the Attorney General.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 2000, the USS Cole is attacked by terrorists. 

At 12:15 p.m. local time, a motorized rubber dinghy loaded with explosives detonated against the USS Cole, a U.S. Navy destroyer refueling in Aden, Yemen. The blast created a 40-by-40-foot hole in the ship's port side, resulting in the deaths of 17 sailors and injuries to 38 others. The attack was executed by two suicide bombers affiliated with al Qaeda, the terrorist network led by Osama bin Laden.

The USS Cole had stopped in Aden to refuel for only four hours, indicating that the attackers had precise and prior knowledge of its unannounced visit. The dinghy managed to blend in with other harbor vessels assisting the Cole during its mooring, allowing the terrorists to approach the warship without raising suspicion. As the dinghy reached the destroyer, it exploded, causing extensive damage to the engine room, mess area, and living quarters.

Witnesses aboard the Cole reported that both attackers stood up just before the explosion, indicating their intention to carry out the deadly mission. This incident marked one of the deadliest attacks against a U.S. naval vessel in recent history and highlighted vulnerabilities in maritime security at foreign ports, prompting significant changes in U.S. naval protocols and counterterrorism efforts in the region. The attack ultimately underscored the growing threat posed by al Qaeda and set the stage for increased tensions between the U.S. and extremist groups in the Middle East.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
This morning, our community came together to honor the life and legacy of a true Bucks County hero‚ÄîPrivate First Class David Wayne Comber, U.S. Army.

A native of Pipersville, David answered the call to serve his country on January 12, 1970, enlisting in the Army at just 18 years old. In September of that year, he deployed to the Republic of South Vietnam, serving on the G2 Mission Target Force at Landing Zone (LZ) Chippewa and with the 3rd Platoon, A Company, 4th Battalion, 3rd Infantry Regiment, 11th Infantry Brigade, Americal Division.

Tragically, on February 15, 1971‚Äîjust five months into his tour‚ÄîDavid‚Äôs unit was ambushed while on patrol in Quang Tri Province, where he sustained fatal wounds. He was only 19 years old.

Today, we honored David‚Äôs memory and sacrifice by dedicating and renaming the bridge on Tollgate Road over Hickory Run Creek in Plumstead Township as a lasting tribute to his service. Thank you to Jim McComb, the Plumstead Township Veterans Committee, and the Township employees and volunteers who made this meaningful tribute possible. Their efforts ensure that the legacy of Private Comber‚Äîand all our brave veterans‚Äîwill never be forgotten.

Name: Alford, Mark
text:
E59: Leaving the USSR: Andrei Kulikov on Chernobyl, Freedom, and the American Spirit

(01:04) Growing Up in the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics (USSR)
(03:04) Serving in the USSR Army & the Chernobyl Disaster
(08:17) Why Did Andrei Leave the USSR?
(10:25) How Did Andrei End Up in Israel?
(12:49) Living in Israel
(13:38) Becoming a United States Citizen
(15:24) Thoughts: Mass Illegal Immigration in 2024
(16:43) Thoughts: Russian invasion of Ukraine
++ much more!

Andrei Kulikov, a former Soviet soldier and now proud U.S. citizen, shares his incredible journey from the USSR to America. He was stationed at Chernobyl shortly after the 1986 nuclear disaster, witnessing the chaos and secrecy surrounding the event. Disillusioned with the Soviet regime, Andrei left in 1989, eventually finding refuge in Israel before making his way to the United States. He speaks passionately about his love for America, admiring the country‚Äôs freedom and its remarkable resilience in the face of challenges. Andrei‚Äôs story is a testament to courage and the pursuit of a better life, offering a perspective lens on the values that define America.

Also available in full on Apple and Spotify Podcasts:
Apple: https://t.co/CWYCh1X1fT
Spotify: https://t.co/AHtZ5H1Giu

Congratulations to Troop 108 on receiving the Centennial Award from the Cradle of Liberty Council‚Äîa well-deserved recognition of your dedication and impact. Thank you to the scouts, leaders, volunteers, and families who have made Troop 108‚Äôs success possible‚Äîyour work ensures that these values will continue to inspire future generations. Name: Scott, Rick
text: Today, I joined President Joe Biden and FEMA Administrator Deanne Criswell on the ground in St. Pete Beach, which was completely destroyed by Hurricane Milton. Like I said following Hurricane Helene, while I appreciate the president and FEMA Administrator coming to Florida to see the devastation firsthand, Floridians are still hurting from storms years ago, and the federal government needs to show up not just today but every day. Not only did storm surge cause significant issues on the coast, but first responders are still conducting non-stop rescue missions as rising rivers cause inland flooding and tornadoes ripped apart entire communities. This storm, along with Hurricane #Helene, has knocked so many communities down, but Floridians are resilient. Following Hurricane Helene, I told President Biden exactly what is needed to ensure Florida has every federal resource to fully recover from that storm and now Hurricane #Milton, I reiterated that in our call last week and again today. Here‚Äôs what I stressed to the President: I‚Äôm calling on Schumer to bring the Senate back ASAP when our communities have assessed their needs, which I told the president must be expedited, to pass needed disaster funding for FEMA, @SBAgov and the USDA and approve common sense relief like my Federal Disaster Tax Relief Act. The president told me he agreed with me on this last week. We must also ensure FEMA opens Disaster Recovery Centers close to the areas hit hardest, so those impacted have easy access to federal resources to recover. Finally, I again stressed to @POTUS the importance of @USDA immediately approving block grants for our farmers that have been struggling since Ian in 2022.¬†I discussed the same things during my calls on Thursday with @FEMA Administrator @FEMA_Deanne Criswell and SBA Administrator @SBAIsabel Casillas Guzman. I‚Äôm going to continue fighting like hell to make sure this happens and aid is delivered to families in need.

Name: Smith, Adam
text:
I am disappointed by Boeing‚Äôs decision to lay off 10 percent of its 170,000-employee workforce over the coming months. This is a hard day for Boeing employees across the world and many of whom reside in King County, Washington. My heart is with those employees and their families who will find themselves out of work.
¬†
Employees are being forced to absorb the consequences of poor corporate management and oversight. In recent years, the company has prioritized profits and stakeholders over the integrity of their product and the well-being of their employees. This strategy is clearly not working. From production delays, faulty parts, stranded astronauts, ongoing litigation, and investigations, Boeing has struggled to produce high quality products.
¬†
This failure has a rippling impact on the nation and the strength of American aerospace. Boeing is a giant legacy aerospace company and the way that they do business impacts not only folks in King County, but also people across the world. Our transportation sector and our national defense rely on the strength of Boeing, but any company is only as strong as its workforce.
¬†
Boeing‚Äôs success relies on its dedicated employees, and investing in them is essential for long-term recovery. Boeing employees have put up with a lot for a long time, from cut pensions to insufficient wage increases. Now more than ever, a fair resolution to the machinists‚Äô strike is essential to restore trust and show commitment to those who drive Boeing‚Äôs future. I sincerely hope that the parties reach an agreement that respects all employees and ensures the strength of the company as a whole.

Name: Suozzi, Thomas R.
text:
Happy Columbus Day! Happy Italian American Heritage Month!

As a first-generation Italian American and member of the Congressional Italian American Caucus, I am proud to have led the bipartisan resolution declaring October as Italian and Italian-American Heritage Month.

My father, Joseph A. Suozzi, had an extraordinary journey. Born in Ruvo del Monte, Italy, he immigrated to the United States as a child, served as a navigator in the U.S. Air Force during World War II, was elected as Glen Cove City Court Judge at the age of 28, and went on to serve as Glen Cove Mayor and was later appointed to the Appellate Division of the N.Y. State Supreme Court. While father‚Äôs story embodies the classic American Dream, he also faced discrimination, as did many Italians, when he returned home from the war..

Today's celebration of Italian heritage, rooted in the challenges that many Italians faced in our history, can and should inspire us to speak out against all forms of hate and discrimination. Let's honor our heritage and our nation‚Äôs rich cultural diversity by promoting inclusivity and understanding.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On this day in 1982, President Ronald Reagan declared illicit drugs a significant threat to U.S. national security. 

The phrase "war on drugs" was initially popularized by Richard Nixon in 1971, but the origins of drug policy in the U.S. can be traced back to the Harrison Narcotics Tax Act of 1914 and the establishment of the Federal Bureau of Narcotics in 1930, reflecting a long history of drug regulation.

In a speech at the Justice Department, Reagan likened his administration‚Äôs commitment to combating drug use and trafficking to the determination shown by the French army during the Battle of Verdun in World War I, stressing that challenges could be overcome with resolve. He quoted a French soldier, asserting, ‚ÄúThere are no impossible situations. There are only people who think they‚Äôre impossible.‚Äù

First Lady Nancy Reagan played a crucial role in spreading the anti-drug message, actively touring elementary schools to educate children about the dangers of drug use. During one visit, when a fourth grader at Longfellow Elementary School in Oakland, California, asked how to respond if offered drugs, she famously replied, ‚ÄúJust say no,‚Äù making the phrase a cultural touchstone.

In 1988, Reagan established the Office of National Drug Control Policy (ONDCP) to coordinate drug-related initiatives across various government sectors, including legislation, security, and health policy. The media dubbed its directors ‚Äúdrug czars,‚Äù reflecting the growing focus on a centralized approach to drug control. In 1993, President Bill Clinton elevated the position to Cabinet-level status, highlighting the ongoing commitment to addressing drug issues at the highest levels of government.

Reagan‚Äôs efforts marked a significant escalation in the War on Drugs, leading to increased funding for drug enforcement and harsher penalties for drug offenses, which contributed to a dramatic rise in incarceration rates for nonviolent drug crimes. This intensified focus on drug policy would have lasting implications for law enforcement and communities across the nation.

Name: Latta, Robert E.
text:
AM radio stations play a critical role in providing emergency alerts, local news, and weather reports for millions of Americans. This underscores the need to strengthen the resiliency of these stations, especially as extreme weather ‚Äì like we've witnessed with hurricanes Helene and Milton ‚Äì threatens to take them offline.

It's encouraging to hear AM radio stations are implementing 21st Century technology to improve and strengthen their operating systems.

Today, I visited one of the more than 70 hardened AM radio stations in the United States - located in Maryland and serving the east coast. As Chair of @HouseCommerce's Communications & Technology Subcommittee, it was important to receive an in-depth look today at this radio station that is putting  this technology to good use.

Congress has a role to play in strengthening our communications systems. And as a member of @HouseCommerce, I'll continue working with my colleagues to advance commonsense legislation that fortifies our critical infrastructure, including AM radio stations, the electric grid, and our telecommunications networks.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text:
Michigan‚Äôs Historic Wage Victory: A Roadmap to Winning Elections in 2024
MI Lieutenant Governor Garlin Gilchrist II, MN Attorney General Keith Ellison, NY Attorney General Tish James, And Congressman Jonathon L. Jackson Join Other Elected Officials, Workers, Employers, and Economic Justice Organizers from Around the Country to Celebrate Michigan‚Äôs Bold Step in Raising Wages and Ending Subminimum Wages
¬†
Media Planning to Attend In Person or Virtually is Kindly Asked to RSVP here
¬†
#Detroit, MI ‚ÄîAs the 2024 elections approach, one issue remains central to both the economy and the path to victory: wages. The rising cost of living has left millions of workers struggling to make ends meet, making jobs with living wages a top priority for working class voters across the country. Just two months ago, the Supreme Court in the battleground state of Michigan made history by ruling to raise wages for 1.2 million workers to $15 by 2028, while also ending the subminimum wage for workers with disabilities, youth and¬† tipped employees‚Äîan outdated and unjust practice that was created after Emancipation to allow restaurants to hire newly-freed Black workers for free. The ruling makes Michigan the first state East of the MIssissippi to end this legacy of slavery.
On October 15, 2024, from 10:00 - 11:00 AM EDT, @onefairwage in collaboration with People‚Äôs Action and @MichiganUnitedAction will bring together Lieutenant Governors, Attorney Generals, national civil rights leaders and representation from various labor and advocacy organizations for a celebration of #Michigan‚Äôs historic victory for workers, uplifting the significance of Michigan‚Äôs leadership on wage reform and the importance of wage equity in this year‚Äôs Presidential election. The event will highlight Michigan‚Äôs leadership role in economic justice, the growing momentum across the country, and how this victory will be a key issue in upcoming elections. The audience will have an opportunity to engage our leaders and engage in meaningful dialog.
WHO:
‚Ä¢Michigan Lieutenant Governor Garlin Gilchrist II
‚Ä¢Minnesota Attorney General @keithellison Ellison
‚Ä¢Congressman Jonathon Jackson (IL-01)
‚Ä¢@PortiaRobeson , Chief Executive Officer, Focus of Hope¬†
‚Ä¢New York Attorney General @TishJames James (virtual)
‚Ä¢Additional labor leaders and workers who will speak about the direct impact of the wage increase and the end of subminimum wages.
¬†
**NOTE: Workers will be available to speak to the media on the importance of wages in their voting decisions in this year‚Äôs Presidential election. **
¬†
WHEN: October 15, 2024, 10:00 - 11:00 AM EDT¬†
WHERE: Please RSVP here. Location details will be provided upon RSVP.¬†
This event marks a pivotal moment in the fight for living wages, as Michigan‚Äôs Supreme Court ruling sets the stage for national wage reform efforts. With the elimination of the subminimum wage for tipped workers‚Äîa practice with roots in systemic inequality‚ÄîMichigan is leading the charge in ensuring fair compensation for all workers. This victory is expected to have broad implications for the labor movement and wage policies across the U.S., particularly as the issue of economic justice takes center stage in the upcoming election cycle. Journalists will have the opportunity to hear directly from elected officials and labor advocates about the next steps in the movement and how other states may follow Michigan‚Äôs lead.
In addition to remarks from the featured speakers, the event will include first hand stories from workers impacted by the wage increase, offering powerful perspectives on how these changes are improving lives and communities.¬†
¬†

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1991, the U.S. Senate confirmed Clarence Thomas to the Supreme Court by a narrow vote of 52 to 48 after a Senate hearing. 

Following the retirement of Thurgood Marshall in July 1991, President George H.W. Bush nominated Thomas, a conservative African American judge. Despite initially facing little opposition, the hearings took a dramatic turn when he was accused of sexual harassment. The televised hearings revealed a stark divide, the testimony met by skepticism from the committee, and Thomas denied the allegations. 

Ultimately, the Senate confirmed Thomas, marking a significant shift toward conservatism in the Supreme Court. Known for his originalist interpretation of the Constitution, Thomas often emphasizes a strict adherence to the text and intent of the framers. He has consistently supported limited government, individual rights, and states' rights, often aligning with fellow conservatives on key issues.

Name: Latta, Robert E.
text:
It was a true honor to present a Bronze Star to Mr. William Young, a Paulding County resident, who honorably served our great nation in the U.S. Army during the Vietnam War. Mr. Young served as one of the members of the 'B' Company, 720th Military Police Battalion, Military Police Brigade.

Mr. Young was trained to be a Military Policeman (MP) but when he arrived in Vietnam, his unit became part of the Bushwhackers whose duties included heading into the jungle to interdict North Vietnamese and Viet Cong troops. And since they were MPs, the Army would not issue them the Combat Infantry Badge. I was pleased to work with the veterans who made up 'B' Company to make sure they received the recognition they deserve - the Bronze Star.

We are forever grateful and indebted to our servicemembers for serving and sacrificing for our people and country.
